{
  "stem": "20021.2",
  "chunk_idx": 1,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 8.5,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "In other words, in some households, they would only eat the shemurah matzah, which was not very tasty and not very easily digestible, as a matter of fact.",
      "word_count": 28
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "But we had both kinds, so that just shows that we were already, so to speak-- my father was not that Orthodox to insist that we all eat only the shemurah matzah.",
      "word_count": 32
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "But my uncle, in his household, I know they would only eat shemurah matzah during Passover.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "In the house, we spoke Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "The parents to us spoke Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "But they spoke to my sister Polish.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And that was a phenomenon which repeated itself again and again.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "It was a rather strange phenomenon.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "We spoke a lot of Polish, but not in the house.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "The parents amongst themselves spoke Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "They spoke to the children, to the sons, Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "But for some reason, to my sister they spoke Polish.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "I don't know how to explain that, but we were not the only ones.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 10,
      "text": "This was quite common.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Well, Yiddish was-- was also sort of part of the-- [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] part of the indoctrination to the Torah was Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "Boys would be spoken to Yiddish because they also studied their Torah, part of it.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "I studied Hebrew and I studied also Yiddish, you know, because studying involved reading a sentence in Hebrew and translating into Yiddish, or else into Hebrew.",
      "word_count": 26
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "I had both ways.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "But girls were excluded from that, excused from that and not included in this sort of-- so-- so that may be why they did not acquire that much Yiddish, and because, you know, the maid would speak to her, because to the maid, they obviously had to speak Polish, because she didn't speak Yiddish.",
      "word_count": 54
    }
  ],
